text:
Northern Boulevard, south side, between Linden Place and Leavitt Street, Flushing, showing an old National Guard Armory. A Friends' Meeting House stood here prior to 1909.

About 1910

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection

Northern Boulevard, at the N. W. corner of Linden Place (right), showing the former Monument Hotel. Charles Fitner sold the hotel to D. Bodenhop in 1884. John E. Prenderville owned it in 1898.

1922

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection

Northern Boulevard, north side, west from Linden Place. The shingled building used as a garage, at the right, was formerly known as Farrington Hall, owned by Nich Gilroy. The Flushing Garage was the owner in 1934. View No. 2 shows from left to right the same buildings owned in 1873 respectively by G. H. Bennett, B.W. Dowing and the Monument Hotel.

1922

Northern Boulevard at the N.E. corner of Linden Street, showing the Flushing Town Hall, now (1926) used as a Kagistrates Court for this area of Queens County.  The cornerstone of this building was laid May 31, 1862.  The old Town Hall occupied the site in the Boulevard where now stands the Fountain and faced on Main Street.  It was destroyed by fire in 1862.
1922.
